english:
  title: A Letter to Minister Choe
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the twelfth month, your humble servant respectfully submits this letter to the esteemed Minister and Grand Scholar.

    When I recently had the honor of visiting your residence, you graciously offered me a seat and showered me with encouragement. You inquired about my recent writings and spoke of the need for talented men in the Chancellery. I was startled and withdrew in gratitude. I am truly unworthy of such regard. My pen lacks the brilliance to honor the realm, and my talent cannot match the expectations of men. Yet you, in your generosity, deem me fit for the duties of a literary minister—a distinction far beyond my deserving. I can only feel shame.

    Yet upon reflection, I have come to understand why this is so. Though your words spring from principle, they come too late. There was a time when you did not dismiss me as unfit. You yourself went to court and submitted a memorial recommending me for placement in the provinces—preparing me, as it were, for future literary service. Your intention was sincere, but fate was unkind and it came to nothing.

    Later, when I had completed the provincial examination, you had just assumed control of the realm's affairs. I thought: if you showed such favor in ordinary times, surely now that power is in your hands, you would not deny me? Yet the years have passed in hardship and obscurity, and your grace has not been extended. Perhaps, like a plain face painted with heavy makeup, I seemed fair at first, but now that the powder has worn away and my true nature is revealed, I cannot hide from your clear mirror's gaze.

    If that is truly so, then so be it. Yet if not, surely your authority could assist me and your favor could reach me. But now the time is different from when I submitted that memorial. Given the present circumstances, it seems I shall never find use in this world. Nothing remains but to return to my fields, work the earth, and sustain my wife and children.

    And yet—I cannot quite surrender this hope, for I retain faith that I might yet prove useful to you. Consider this: when a man sees another suffering in poverty but lacks the means to help, he appeals earnestly to a wealthy family, begging for even a pittance to relieve the crisis. But the wealthy man proves stingy and refuses. Later, when the poor man becomes as rich as his former would-be benefactor, does he not think: "Since I had no means to help him then, surely now that I am wealthy, he will not refuse me?" He becomes confident that the rich man will share his gold and treasure.

    Such is the poor man's reasoning. But what if the wealthy man happens to forget and does not give? Should the poor man then rage and depart immediately? Or should he wait a while, observing? How would you handle such a matter? It seems to me one should bear it a moment longer, divining whether the man has truly forgotten, and only then depart with grace. It is not yet too late.

    Yet I confess this impatience of mine—this urgency to seize the moment—may itself be premature. Surely your heart would not condemn me to endless poverty. How do I know this? Because I once composed verses in response to your praise of a stone gift from Commissioner Qi. When you were dining, you set down your spoon, abandoned your meal, and recited my poem without ceasing, so that your steward was moved to chide the servant who brought it to you. I did not hear of this through rumor alone—your youngest son told me of it himself.

    By this I am certain: you have not forgotten me.

    What grieves me is that my years press toward the meridian of life. A scholar does not enter service merely to advance his own glory and rank. Rather, he seeks to apply what he has learned to governance, to wield strategies of state and statecraft, to serve the throne with his talents, and to leave a name that endures a hundred generations. Yet consider the ranks of office: there are nine grades, with distinctions I need not enumerate. Beyond these are various probationary positions. Even within the nine grades, there are differences of seniority. Provincial posts—magistrates, commanders, garrison officers—do not accord with the ranks of the capital, yet they require three years of service before rotation. Thus advancement in the provinces moves far more slowly than in the capital.

    A man may live a hundred years, yet few reach seventy. Even to ascend a single grade at thirty is considered late. I am already thirty-seven. Since youth, I have been frail and often ill. By thirty-four, my hair had turned white. Though I pluck it out, it grows back endlessly. Now black and white are equal in number. Like a tree about to wither, its leaves must first change. How many years remain to me?

    Nearing the end of my years, I have yet to receive even a single probationary post. The path of official advancement is long and arduous, and the years I have left to serve my country grow shorter still. If I do not attain office until forty, I shall barely reach the sixth or seventh rank before my hair is entirely white—and so my life ends. Moreover, nothing from without can be assured. Even rank six or seven cannot be guaranteed. How can I then aspire to high office and wield the strategies of statecraft? Where, then, shall I practice serving my nation? What reward awaits my labors? What name shall I leave to posterity? This is why I rise three times in the night and gaze at heaven with great sighs.

    Now that you hold the mirror's clarity and preside over the selection of officials, all men's worth or unworthiness is revealed in your penetrating light, and none dare conceal even a hair's breadth of deception. How much more so with me—for my service in your company has not been brief. My words and deeds, crooked or straight, you already know in detail. I have offered my writings to you two or three times; you have already judged their merit or deficiency. You have heard of my work in Wansan. If you say I have not yet fulfilled my probation, I accept it. But regarding my dismissal—that was due to false accusations by colleagues. The rights and wrongs, the justice and injustice, the integrity and corruption are now clear. I need not defend myself; surely you have long known the truth.

    Why, then, do you hesitate? Why do you rely on doubt and fail to decide?

    I hear there is a vacancy in the Chancellery. If you would temporarily appoint me and test what I have learned, and if I fail to prove worthy, then dismiss me and I shall harbor no resentment. For surely it is better to test than to judge without trial; surely it is better to speak fully and regret afterward than to remain silent and regret forever. This is why I dare to speak thus—hoping that you will first test whether I am able.

    Alas, my fortune and ruin, life and death, advance and retreat all rest in your hands. I await your word. Do not let me be forgotten like that wealthy man, condemned to endless hardship. I write in trepidation and awe. More I cannot say.

    Your humble servant respectfully bows.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'mirror' (水鏡) is a traditional metaphor for an official's clear judgment and discernment in evaluating talent.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The elaborate parable of the poor and wealthy man illustrates Lee Gyubo''s anxiety: having been promised advancement that never materialized, he questions whether Minister Choe will now forget him entirely or finally deliver on past promises.'
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gyubo's frustration stems from the long timescale of Korean bureaucratic advancement—three years in provincial posts before rotation, and the realization that his aging body and graying hair mean he may never rise to high enough position to accomplish great deeds before death.
  - key: ''
    value: Wansan (完山) is an ancient name for Jeonju, where Lee Gyubo had served in an administrative capacity.
